  "original_title": "Sri Lanka needs quick fiscal reforms, political stability: Central Bank union",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka needs quick fiscal reforms, political stability: Central Bank union",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka needs to accelerate fiscal reforms to bring back economic stability, and a stable government to carry them out, the Central Bank Executive Officers\u2019 Union has warned, as monetary instability and forex shortages continue and attempts are made to appoint a new President.",
        "Though a new cabinet was appointed after protests on May 09, essential fiscal reforms have not happened for the past two months, the Union pointed out.",
        "Delayed tax hikes would make high interest rates persist for a longer time, analysts say.",
        "There are expectations that under a program endorsed by the International Monetary Fund, the required co-ordinated minimum fiscal and monetary policy changes would be made.",
        "Of late all those in power have agreed that an IMF program is required, the Union said.",
        "\u201cTo regain economic stability, there has to be some basic economic and political program that all parties can agree to,\u201d the Union said.",
        "\u201cWe would like to re-iterate that all parties should leave aside individual agendas and get together around a mechanism that can find solutions to the economic crisis.\u201d",
        "However the current parliament\u2019s majority may not reflect public opinion and there are doubts whether a President chosen by the parliament would be able to garner public support for very long time, the Union said.",
        "As a result it may be best to go for elections as soon as stability is reached.",
        "The Union also called for the enactment of a Central Bank reform bill drawn up by a previous leadership which would give more independence to the Central Bank to carry out policy as it wished.",
        "However analysts had warned that the drafted law does not bring any constitutional restraint to the Central Bank and will give it carte blanche to carry out contradictory money and exchange policies that trigger currency crises in quick succession, as had happened from 2015 to 2022.",
        "The draft law seeks to legitimise a reserve collecting peg, called a flexible exchange rate, which is neither a hard peg nor a free float, while also trying to operate an inflation targeting framework with open market operations despite the lack of floating exchange rate.",
        "Under the similar framework, a currency crises was triggered despite the budget deficit being brought down and fuel being market priced in 2018 (de facto fiscal dominance of monetary policy also being taken away).",
        "Due to liquidity injections to suppress interest rates under flexible policy, IMF reserve targets were missed, the currency fell and triggered political instability, critics have said.",
        "IMF programs, while bringing countries out of currency crises (a problem associated with non-floating flexible exchange rates or soft-pegs) do not bring permanent solutions since reserve collection and pegging is perpetuated.",
        "\u2018Flexible\u2019 inflation targeting is practiced in Latin America (Argentina was targeting 17-pct flexible inflation during its last currency crisis and default) and is not practiced by stable reserve currency central banks. (Colombo/July18/2022)"
      ],
